Restoring the very American ideal that labour rights are also human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis proposed a bill to protect union organizing as a civil right.
“The way the unions work, the middle-class jobs work,” says Ellison, a Democratic senator from Minnesota who is co-chair of the Congressional Committee.
That’s why I’m so proud to introduce the Employee Empowerment Act alongside John Lewis’ occasional rights model.
This ground-breaking legislation will give workers the same legal options to resist discrimination in union organizing as with other forms of discrimination - and stop anti-union forces
Modifying the Labor Relations Act to allow all employees who face discrimination to join unions, to sue in a civil court - and to sue for compensation or damages - is the right and necessary initiative.
But this is certainly not a radical initiative - at least not by American standards.
The best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis, and other proponents of the law are proposing is to re-establish the American ideal.
Despite the labor struggles that have taken place in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states - Americans once supported countries around the world to embrace, extend, and respect labor rights.
There was a time, and millions of Americans still remember it, when the country stood for democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right to assemble in one breath.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his advisers encouraged the country to adopt a constitution designed to ensure that the military autocracy of Hideki Toja was replaced by democracy.
Convinced that workers and their unions played a role in shaping the new Japan, they included language in them and openly acknowledged that "the right of employees to assemble, collectively negotiate and act is guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his advisers urged the Germans to create a constitution to ensure that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Realizing that workers would need to organize and promote themselves in the new nation, the Germans included a clause that openly states: “The right to form associations which will secure and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every individual and to every profession or profession.
Agreements that restrict this right or seek to damage it will be revoked. Measures to fulfill such a purpose are illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Commission on Human Rights that drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which was adopted by the United Nations as a global treaty in 1948, the drafters and Roosevelt's guarantee included in it that "everyone has the right to form and join unions in order to protect their interests."
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When the country advised other countries on how to create a civil and democratic society, the Americans explained that the right to create labor unions - and their participation in collective bargaining with companies and government agencies as equal partners - must be protected.
Now that these rights are being challenged in America, it is definitely necessary to return to the American ideal that working people must have the right to organize and assert themselves in a free and open society.
As Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said 50 years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Today, everyone knows that the trade unions have not diminished the strength of the nation, but have expanded it.
They have raised the standard of living of millions of people, created a market for industry and raised production to an unsuspected level.
Those who attack unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History does not forget, and neither should we.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of civil rights to prevent discrimination in the organisation of trade unions - is greatly delayed.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are renewing the ideals that have elevated America and made it a true promise of democracy.
Judge Temporarily Blocks Law That Could Shut Down All Louisiana Abortion Clinics
A federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked a Louisiana law that would likely shut down all five abortion clinics in the state, according to lawyers.
The bill, signed into law by Louisiana Governor Bobby Jindal in June and due to enter into force on September 1, would require abortion practitioners to have the right to admit a patient to a hospital within 30 miles of their practice.
The judge’s decision means that doctors can temporarily continue to perform legal abortions and must obtain this permission in the meantime.
“The proposing party will be able to legally carry out its activities and in the meantime obtain a permit,” federal judge John deGravelles said in a statement.
The hearing will be scheduled within one month so that the judge can issue a more permanent resolution regarding the bill.
Abortion rights activists welcomed the resolution, which is the latest in a series of similar measures, saying it would give doctors more time to obtain a permit.
“Today’s decision ensures that women in Louisiana are safe from a sneaky law that would deprive them of their health and rights,” Nancy Northup, president and executive director of the Center for Reproductive Rights, said in a statement.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision also applies to doctors from two clinics that were not among the plaintiffs, and they also apply for this permission.
Louisiana is among eleven states that have passed similar laws, with courts in Alabama and Mississippi declaring such measures unconstitutional by provision.
Key parts of Texas law that would close most of the remaining clinics in the state were blocked by federal judges on Friday.
Women's rights activists, together with the American Obstetricians and Gynecologists Association and the American Medical Association, say the need for this license places medical demands on doctors that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortion have argued that the measures are aimed at protecting women's health, and some have also welcomed the fact that the clinics would be closed because of the measures.
The Center for Reproductive Rights said only one doctor performing abortions is allowed in Louisiana.
If all doctors in the state were forced to stop performing abortions, this doctor would also stop performing the procedure for fear of his safety, the group said.
In response, Louisiana authorities said they would not punish doctors who perform abortions while waiting to process a request for rights.
