For black women like Mitchell, who have dealt with the issue of race, gender, and sexuality in American history, there is no dichotomy between the issues of race and gender.
Black women, she said, could not afford the luxury of clearly dividing these problems: every day they live in this mixed reality.
Although white women today combine the issue of race and gender in mainstream feminist circles, Angela Hattery, a professor lecturing on the women's issue and gender studies at George Mason University, says their predecessors did the opposite.
"Between 1865 and 1890, at least 10,000 blacks were lynched, and the reason for this was almost all rapes of white women," Hattery said.
You needed the cooperation of a white woman to justify the lynching.
