“They decided to bet on the right to vote for women and to focus on the right for blacks later,” Hattery said.
When we realize this, we get an important insight into why women of color don't trust white women.
We didn't do a good job.
We never helped black women protect their husbands and children.
Even after women gained the right to vote in 1920, it took ten years to start organizing against lynching in the Association of Southern Women to prevent lynching.
The group was formed 40 years after black women first asked for help.
According to Mitchell, the upsurge in white feminist responses to the issues raised by Ferguson - the issue of police behavior, racial discrimination - reflects a time when white feminists had to "catch up" with the issues that black women have faced for generations.
“Wouldn’t it be great if activists in these spaces [traditional feminism] took the right to raise a child as seriously as they took the right to contraception?” she asked.
The second wave of feminists who have made careers fighting for reproductive rights and access to contraception are now figuring out what that means.
Prominent feminist activists such as Gloria Steinem took Facebook two weeks after the shooting of Michael Brown, where they published a column by Rebecca Carroll of the Guardian calling for white Americans to protest racism more vigorously.
