Although the Labour Code does not impose the obligation to have the employer’s consent to take leave confirmed in writing, in practice this procedure has proven itself.
If there is only an oral agreement, you do not have a confirmation of the agreement.
Later, the alleged consent to take leave, as in your case, can be considered a long-term unexcused absence from work, thus a reason for immediate termination of employment under Section 53 of the Labor Code.
In the event of a legal dispute with your employer, you will lack demonstrable proof.
However, the employment relationship with you has not been terminated under section 53, you only have the given days listed in the credit card as an unexcused absence.
An unexcused absence from the credit card does not have the same consequences as Section 53 (e.g. the impossibility of obtaining material security in unemployment), yet it makes it difficult to find a new job.
We recommend that you visit the doctor again and have him/her confirm in writing that an accident has really occurred, as a result of which you were unable to work (this is not a so-called "inability to work", it is only a doctor's document).
When looking for a new job, you can present the document and explain the situation.
