Why the Universe Can Have More Dimensions and We Can't See Them
Physicists don't usually write best-sellers, but Brian Green of Columbia University managed to hit the jackpot in 1999.
His book The Elegant Universe has become the most accessible way for laymen to get to the thicket of problems that many theoretical physicists are now dealing with - an attempt to unite two well-functioning but incompatible discoveries of the 20th century: quantum theory and the theory of general relativity.
One of the reasons for the success of the Elegant Universe is undoubtedly that the search for a unified physical theory is not a boring story.
Physicists have solved the fundamental problem between two key theories (for at the moment our universe is de facto divided into two worlds with different laws) and solve it so imaginatively that it is worth retelling even to laymen.
In addition, Greene dealt with the complex material so fresh and engaging that it is impossible to blame him for how much interesting he did not include in his book.
In addition, he corrected his "mistake" for the most part in two other books: The Structure of the Universe and Hidden Reality.
Perhaps the author would not object to his book becoming obsolete faster, but the fact is that even after 15 years, the Elegant Universe still provides almost everything essential that an informed layman with an ambition to understand the world should know about this important part of theoretical physics.
It is quite likely that in the coming years it will be a bit more lively in this area (for example, because the LHC accelerator will finally go on "full gas"), so it is a good time to enter the non-violently open door of the world of modern physics by Greene.
How many dimensions can our universe have?
The idea that our universe may have more than three spatial dimensions can certainly sound foolish, fantastic, strange or mystical.
However, it is specific and completely acceptable.
To understand this, let us turn our eyes away from the universe as a whole for a moment to something more mundane, namely a long and thin garden hose for watering.
Imagine that you stretch a hundred-meter garden hose from one side of the canyon to the other and watch the whole scenery from a half-kilometer distance (as in the picture and on the next page).
From such a distance, you can easily detect a long, horizontally stretched hose, but if you do not suffer from sharpness, you can hardly tell the thickness of the hose.
Because of its great distance from the hose, you would think that an ant forced to live on the hose has only one dimension in which to walk: the left-right dimension along the hose.
When someone asks you where the ant was at a given moment, you answer with only one indication: the distance of the ant from the left (or right) end of the hose.
All we want to say is that from a distance of half a kilometer, a long piece of hose looks like a one-dimensional object.
In the real world, the hose is thick.
If we enlarge everything, we suddenly see a second dimension - in the shape of a circle wrapping the hose.
In such an enlarged view, it is obvious that the ant can actually move in two independent dimensions: in the already well-known left-right dimension along the length of the hose, but also in the "dimension in/against the direction of movement of the clock hands", that is, around the circular cross-section of the hose.
You are beginning to understand that to determine the position of a small ant, you need to enter two numbers: how far is it from the end of the hose and where is the circle wrapping the hose.
This reflects the fact that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional (Experts note that this chapter focuses purely on broken string theory.
These are discussed in Chapters 12 and 13.)
The surface of the hose is two-dimensional: one long longitudinal dimension is shown by a straight arrow, the dimension in the direction of the perimeter, marked with a circular arrow, is short and coiled.
However, there is a clear difference between these two dimensions.
The dimension along the hose is long and easily visible.
The dimension wrapping the circumference of the hose is short, "twisted" and less noticeable.
To realize the existence of a circular dimension, we had to examine the hose with significantly better resolution.
This example illustrates an important feature of spatial dimensions.
That they divide into two groups.
They can be either large, sprawling and therefore directly visible, or on the contrary small, coiled and much more difficult to observe.
Of course, in the above case, we did not just push ourselves to reveal the "twisted" dimension wrapping the thickness of the hose.
Just take a telescope to help.
But if the hose were thinner - like a hair or capillary - we would only reveal the coiled dimension with great effort.
Kaluza sent Einstein an article in 1919, in which he came up with the amazing idea that the spatial geometry of the universe could have more than three known dimensions.
Kaluza's radical claim was justified by the fact that the extra dimension provides an elegant and compelling framework within which Einstein's general relativity and Maxwell's electromagnetic theory can be woven into a single, unified conceptual structure.
Immediately the question arises how this Kaluza observation goes together with the obvious fact that we see just three dimensions of space.
The answer, which Kaluza quietly assumed between the lines and which was clearly expressed and specified by the Swedish mathematician Oskar Klein in 1926, stands and falls with the claim that the spatial geometry of our universe can have both large and coiled dimensions.
This means that just like dimensions in the direction of the length of the hose, our universe has a large, vast and easily visible three dimensions, the existence of which we are aware of every moment.
But by analogy with the circular circumference of the garden hose, the universe can have even additional dimensions, tightly coiled into space so tiny that they have so far remained hidden even from our most perfect experimental apparatuses.
To get a clearer idea of the essence of Kaluza's remarkable design, let's stay with the hose for a while.
Imagine drawing a fairly dense row of circles on the circumference of the hose in black.
The outside of the hose still looks like a thin one-dimensional line.
With the telescope, we will now reveal the coiled dimension even more easily thanks to the drawing, because we will see the motif from Figure 2.
We can clearly see that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional, with one dimension large and almost unlimited, and with the other short and circular.
Kaluza and Klein came up with the idea that our universe has a similar structure, but apart from one small circular dimension, it has three large spatial dimensions, together, four spatial dimensions.
It is difficult to draw an object with too many dimensions.
To help our imaginations a little, let us note the illustrations in Figure 3; it shows two large dimensions and one small circular dimension.
In the picture, we enlarge the view of the geometry of space in a similar way as we have enlarged the surface of the hose.
Each subsequent level represents a huge increase in the geometry of the space from the previous level.
Our universe can have additional dimensions (we see them at the fourth level of magnification) if they are coiled into a sufficiently small space; this explains that we have not yet directly observed them.
The square grid depicts commonly known "big" dimensions, while the circle represents a new, tiny, and coiled dimension.
Just like the loops of threads in a densely woven carpet, these circles exist in every place of the usual size - just for the sake of illustration, we have drawn them only to the intersections in the square mesh.
The background of Figure 4 shows a commonly known structure of space - the ordinary world around us - in such common scales as meters,shown by the side of a small square in a square grid.
In each of the following images, we will focus on a small area of the previous image; we will enlarge it to make it visible.
At first, nothing special happens, as we see in the first few levels of magnification.
But as we move beyond the microscopic properties of space geometry - to the fourth level of magnification in Figure 3 - we suddenly see a new, coiled dimension in the shape of a circle, similar to a loop of thread in a densely woven piece of carpet.
Kaluza and Klein came up with the idea that an additional circular dimension exists at every point in the direction of the large dimensions, much like a hose has a circular circumference at every point of its length.
For the sake of clarity, we have drawn a circular dimension only in some regularly spaced points.
Figure 4 summarizes Kaluza and Klein's idea of the microscopic structure of space geometry.
The similarity with the hose is obvious, although we also notice important differences.
First, the universe has three large, far-reaching spatial dimensions (of which we have drawn only two), while the hose has a large dimension of only one.
An even more important difference is that we are now talking about the spatial geometry of the universe itself, not just some object inside the universe, like our hose.
But the basic idea is the same.
If the additional circularly coiled dimension is extremely miniature, to recognize it - as well as the circular circumference of the hose - is much more difficult than to observe the obvious, large and sprawling dimensions.
If the size of the extra dimension is small enough, it will actually reveal it beyond the power of our state-of-the-art enlargement tools.
But the most important thing is that the extra dimension is not just a round bump inside the normal dimensions, as the two-dimensional illustration erroneously suggests.
The circular dimension is a new dimension that exists at every point of three common vast dimensions.
It is a dimension on the other three dimensions as independent as the top-down, left-right, and front-back dimensions are independent (and perpendicular) of each other.
A sufficiently small anteater could move in all four dimensions, and to determine its position we would need four data, in addition to the three usual positions in the circular dimension; if we also count the time, then the data five, in any case one more than we would normally expect.
