To our surprise, therefore, we find that although we are aware of the existence of only three dimensions of space, Kaluza and Klein's reasoning shows that this does not exclude the existence of additional coiled dimensions, if they are small enough.
The universe may have more dimensions than can be seen with the naked eye.
How small should they be?
State-of-the-art technical equipment can recognize structures of a billionth of a billionth of a meter.
We can barely observe the smaller coiled dimensions.
In 1926, Klein combined Kaluza's original idea with several ideas from the newly emerging quantum mechanics.
His calculations suggested that the extra circular dimension might be about one Planck length, far beyond the resolution of today's instruments.
Since then, physicists have called the possibility of additional tiny spatial dimensions a Kaluza-Klein theory.
