The Smart Way to Save for College Scripts
Since the cost of college textbooks for many students exceeds $1,000 per year, an upcoming second-year student has come up with a clever way to cut costs.
He devised a system of borrowing books from high school classmates with an offer of nominal compensation to delay their sale back.
“I got a math book that normally costs $180 for a semester for ten and chicken nuggets,” says Schroeder, 19, who studies at Covenant College in Georgia.
The books required in his final semester would cost $430, he says.
He spent 120.
According to the university council, the average student spends more than $1,200 per year on textbooks and aids, but students have various options to manage these expenses.
Online shops and creative solutions such as Schroeder’s are becoming the preferred choice for students.
Lending textbooks is on the rise, allowing students to use the book for a semester, often at a significant discount than if they had bought it.
Neebo Inc, which operates more than 250 bookstores on campuses, says book lending has doubled since 2011.
The survey shows that about a quarter of books in university bookstores were borrowed in the last spring semester, says Neebo vice president Trevor Meyer.
Less than half of the learning texts are bought in university bookstores, according to the National Association of University Shops.
Here are the 101 best ways to succeed.
Online shopping
The prices of some new books can be up to a third lower on the Internet than in a university bookstore.
The recommended price for the ninth edition of "Calculus" by Ron Larson, Bruce Edwards and Robert Hostetler is almost $290, but on the Internet it is possible to buy a new one at Chegg.com, a bookstore specializing in textbooks, for $239.99.
Buy used
If you don’t mind other people’s comments or wear and tear, the learning texts used are a good option.
On Chegg.com, "Calculus" sells for $93.49.
Matt Casaday, 25, a senior student at Brigham Young University, says he paid 42 cents on Amazon.com for a used copy of “Strategic Media Decisions: Understanding The Business End Of The Advertising Business.”
The new one sold for $48.
University lecturer Ingrid Bracey, head of the University of Massachusetts Amherst's College Without Walls, suggests that students check with their tutors to see if older editions are acceptable.
Sometimes changes are not important for working in seminars.
If yes, older editions can be sold for a fraction of the price of the latest version.
In addition to Chegg and Amazon, eBay Inc's Half.com is also a popular alternative to buying used books.
Lending
Borrowing textbooks is also worth considering, if you treat them well, do not forget to return them and do not need to have them even after the end of the seminar.
You can save up to 80% of the cost of a new book.
For example, a student could borrow “Calculus” for about twenty dollars for the entire semester.
Learn about the terms and conditions of the store where you borrow the book, including penalties for notes, highlights, or wear and tear and damage.
Keep in mind: If you don’t return the book in time, the fine may be higher than the price of the new book.
E-books
Another option is to get an e-book instead of a normal book.
Sometimes these books are essentially borrowed in the form of electronic licenses valid for a certain period of time from distributors such as Amazon.com, Chegg, and Barnes & Noble Inc.
Chegg lends Calculus for six months for about $61.
Thus, according to Bracey, the most advantageous offers can be found by students of literary courses, since many classics are now available for free download, while natural and technical texts can be very expensive.
In any case, go to the shops.
Joe Gault, 29, who will soon be joining Pepperdine Law School, recommends following the ISBN as it guarantees you are buying the right book.
Before you order a book over the internet, make sure it’s really in stock, advises Gault.
He was convinced of it on his own skin.
The book he bought sold out for four weeks, and he had to pay the full price for the book from the university bookstore.
