Putin asks Kiev to open talks on “state sovereignty” with eastern Ukraine
Russian President Vladimir Putin on Sunday asked the Ukrainian government to stop fighting separatists in the east of the country and immediately begin negotiations on “state sovereignty” of the breakaway areas.
His spokesman Dmitry Peskov later explained that Putin’s remark was not intended to imply that areas of eastern Ukraine controlled by the separatists would become part of Russia, but that their status within Ukraine should be reconsidered so that the Russian-speaking region would be given authority to protect its rights and interests.
Putin’s call on the Kiev government to treat the pro-Russian rebels as equals is in line with the apparent strategy it has been following since the riots broke out five months ago: Help the separatists occupy the territory and force the Ukrainian government to grant the newly proclaimed Novorossiya de facto independence so that instead of joining the West, it can join Russia.
In an interview on state television, Putin condemned Ukraine’s military actions to retake the eastern regions of Donetsk and Luhansk, which were taken over by separatists in March and April after Moscow annexed Ukraine’s Crimean peninsula on March 18.
The Kremlin and separatists referred to the recently occupied territory as “Novorossiya” or “New Russia”, a term that refers to the famous pre-revolutionary days of the Russian Empire.
The Russian news agency Itar-Tass published Putin’s words, according to which the “prisoner of illusion” is anyone who believes that peace negotiations are on the horizon, because Ukrainian politicians launched campaigns before the parliamentary elections on October 26, while government troops are attacking the civilian population in areas controlled by separatists.
“In the interest of the people living in these areas, we must immediately start meaningful negotiations, not only on legal matters, but also on the political organization of society and the status of state sovereignty of the south-east of Ukraine,” he said.
Peskov said Putin’s allusion to state sovereignty was meant in the context of broader autonomy, which has been under discussion with Kiev’s leadership for several months, and which is intended to alleviate Russian-speaking areas’ concerns about threats to cultural and linguistic rights.
Peskov said that only the Ukrainian government can grant the necessary autonomy to the eastern regions.
This is not a matter for discussion between Ukraine and Russia, Peskov said, “because it is not a conflict between Russia and Ukraine, but an internal Ukrainian conflict.”
The Kremlin spokesman’s move to correct the “misinterpretation” of Putin’s remarks underscored the Russian leadership’s approach to resolving the separatist insurgency in the east, which is different from the open occupation of Crimea, where most of the population of two million is ethnic Russians.
Moscow would have much more trouble annexing Donetsk and Luhansk in eastern Ukraine, as most of Ukraine’s 6.5 million residents are not Russians, and opinion polls conducted before the conflict showed widespread support for remaining in Ukraine.
The autonomy that Russian diplomats discussed in international forums would give regional governments in Ukraine the power to determine their own trade agreements and international relations, essentially giving the Kremlin de facto control over the territory that would link the Russian mainland with Crimea.
The Black Sea Peninsula, annexed five months ago, is home to Russia’s main naval fleet, maritime trade facilities, and historic coastal resorts.
The areas between Rostov and Crimea are also the center of mines, factories and foundries that produce important components for the Russian army.
During his inaugural address on 7 June, Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko proposed that Ukrainian lawmakers - after new elections - consider changes to the constitution that would give diverse regions more control over their finances and language status.
But this vision of autonomy differs greatly from that of the Kremlin and the separatists, and Moscow is accused of arming and inciting violence.
Putin’s latest call for Kiev to treat the separatists as equals followed the rebels’ further advance last week after Russian troops and tanks from a previously peaceful area along the Sea of Azov invaded eastern Ukraine.
The separatists, strengthened by the Russians, have taken control of Novoazovsk by such force that the Ukrainian security authorities fear that it is a campaign to occupy the strategic coastal territory as far as Crimea.
This hastened a huge civilian and military effort to fortify Mariupol, a port with 500,000 inhabitants of metallurgical combined, which lies between Novoazovsk and the narrow entrance gate to the Crimean peninsula.
Poroshenko spoke at a meeting of European Union leaders in Brussels on Saturday and called for action to prevent further Russian aggression against Ukraine, a former Soviet republic that has been independent for the past 23 years.
“We are approaching a point of no return,” Poroshenko warned.
There are now thousands of foreign military units and hundreds of foreign tanks on the territory of Ukraine.
The EU summit has not taken any definitive action - leaders are calling for further sanctions against Russia in the event of an unspecified escalation of the Ukrainian crisis.
Colonel Andriy Lysenko, a spokesman for Ukraine’s National Security and Defense Council, told reporters in Kiev on Saturday that Ukrainian troops had to withdraw from their positions in Ilovaisk after two columns of Russian armored vehicles and 1,000 military units broke into the Donetsk region last week to support besieged separatists.
The first of the 63 reported Ukrainian soldiers captured in Ilovaisk during the Russian invasion were exchanged on Sunday for 10 Russian paratroopers captured a week ago in the interior of Ukraine, Lysenko said on Sunday.
